NeuronArray.networkNotes: Purpose: The Perception Network represents the sensory and recognition half of the neocortex, the other half (frontal) being planning and action. This network approaches intelligence from the level of a three-year-old—it can recognize objects and associate words with them. This is a necessary component of general intelligence. This network utilizes the UKS to recognize visual objects, determine their properties and relationships, and associate these with descriptive words. Along the way, this network has modules for boundary and corner detection, determination of areas, recognition of shapes, colors, and known objects. Physical objects have properties of which color and shape are more-or-less absolute while others such as size and position are only meaningful in relationship to other objects. Armed with this information, the network can detect which objects in a visual field are moving and determine if it is object motion or a change in point of view. In order to do this, the system introduces the concept of “Attention” with the idea that in order to determine the relationships between objects (e.g. bigger/smaller, lighter/darker) the mind needs to know which objects are being compared. In this instance, the system can pay attention to a single visual object at a time and relationships are created between the two most recent objects of attention. Likewise, the system can pay attention to a single audible (word) input at a time. Finally, the network associates word input with the various properties. Over time and repetition, the system can learn the names of colors and shapes and various relationships. The UKS:The UKS is a collection of “nodes” connected by “edges” which are loosely comparable to neurons connected by synapses. For details see the documentation or the Neural Graph networkIn this context, nodes are called “Things” and edges are “Links.” Things can have labels for reference and Links can have a weight. For convenience, some edges create parent/child relationships so the tree structure can be built. In general, you can think of a parent relationship as an “is-a” relationship. After starting the engine (more details below), you’ll be able to see that Thing c0 is-a Color which is-a Visual Thing which is-a sense which is-a Thing because everything is a Thing. The UKS also supports a number of searching functions such as: get the highest-weighted Link which points to a Thing which has a parent of “Color”. This is the type of search your brain does to answer the question: “What color is this?”Any desired information structure can be built within the UKS and the structure implemented in this network is a best-guess of how information might be organized in the brain. Within the UKS is a mental model of the current surroundings. When objects are recognized, they are added to the mental model. Attention can move from object to object in the mental model. Information Concepts:There are a few fundamental concepts needed to understand how this network (or a brain) must work. Consider the brain to be a huge UKS with many millions of nodes. Here are a few terms which define mechanisms implemented in that structure.Object: a physical object which is represented as a Thing. For example, in your field of view there might be a blue square.Property: an object may have any number of properties. Blue and Square would be properties of the node representing the object which you see. Usually a property is represented as a Link to another Thing. Accordingly, there is a Thing representing Blue and another representing Square.Value: some properties have values. The position of an object in your field of view is represented by the x and y coordinate of the retinal cells which fire from the image of that object. These values are transient as a particular object will be at a different position in your eye if your eye moves so the value is not a property of the object but only of the current appearance of the object. Different values are likewise represented by Things—for convenience within the UKS, the value of the Thing is shown in its label.Relationships: most information in the brain is stored in the form of Relationships. You don’t know how big something is, you only know that it is bigger/smaller/same-sized as something else. Biological neurons can be vastly more precise at detecting a Relationship than at storing a Value. Whereas Values and Properties can be represented as a single Link between two Things, a Relationship needs to add a Relationship Type. This allows your brain to answer questions like “What are some things which are the same color as this thing?” where “same color” would be the relationship type.Associations: Links between disparate types of information are not properties, values, or relationships. The Thing representing the word “Red” can be associated with the abstract red-colored-Thing but the word has no intrinsic relationship whatsoever with the color. The Association is built up by repeated simultaneous occurrences of the word and the visual Thing. To create associations, the UKS implements the idea of “Firing” for Things. When a word or a visual object is detected, its related Thing fires. Now a search for most-recently-fired Things which are descendants of a Visual Thing can be matched with a similar search for descendants of a Word Thing to build Associations.Things to try:All of the information is stored in the UKS. The content of the UKS is shown as a tree in the dialog which is front and center in the network. You can expand the various branches of the tree to watch it evolve. When your mouse cursor is in the UKS dialog, it stops updating and its background turns light blue to remind you that the visible content is no longer current. When your mouse cursor leaves the dialog window, it resumes updating.Note that under “Senses” are “Visual”, “Touch”, and “Audible”. Touch is not used in this demonstration. Start the neuron engine. You’ll see a number of items update in the UKS dialog including an item labelled “ATTN” which references Area0. This means that the system is currently paying attention to Area0. Since this is the only object in the visual field, the system pays attention to it continuously. When there are multiple objects in the visual field, the system will pay attention to them randomly. As the system learns the meanings of the properties and relationships in the mental model, it begins to have an “internal monologue” where it verbally describes the current attention object.Expand the properties under Sense | Visual | Color to see that a color labeled “c0” has been created. You and I know it represents blue because we can see the blue triangle in the visual field, but at this time, the UKS has no way of knowing what it represents. When you expand c0, you’ll see that it has references to three things and is referenced by three others. It references the value things for its Hue, Saturation, and Luminance and it is referenced by Area0 which is in the visual field (which is transient), another Area0 which is in the mental model, and KnownShape0 which is in the library of known shapes.To begin building associations, go to the text box in the “Description Module” dialog, type the words “blue triangle”, and press “OK”. Now, c0 is also referenced by the words wTriangle and wBlue. The numbers following the entries show the numbers of “hits” and “misses” which is used to calculate the weight for the association. Entering training data this way is tedious so there is an automated way of presenting images of shapes and their descriptions to exercise the network. The Image File Module dialog can be used to navigate to a different image. In this case, click the “…” button and navigate to TestData\SingleShapes\ and choose the yellow rectangle. You’ll see the color “c1” created. It will automatically have a few words associated with it because the system defaults to using the file name as words for the description.The system uses images which are 100x100 .png’s built with MS-Paint. These are necessarily simple. If you expand Visual | Shape| Area, you see two saved shapes: SavedShape0 contains three corners and SavedShape1 has four. You can also expand Visual | CurrentlyVisible and see that Area0 references SavedShape1 and c1. Under Visual | KnownObjects, there are two things, one referencing SavedShape0 and c0 which is the blue triangle we saw previously while the other is the yellow rectangle we can see now.In the Image File Module Dialog, check the box “Auto Cycle all files in folder”. You’ll see the system cycle through the files in the folder using the file names as the descriptions. As the system runs, you can see Things firing in the UKS and many Association references will be added, many of which are incorrect. This is because when you hear words and see objects, you have no way of knowing which words apply to which properties. Your brain (and the system) has no alternative but to store them all and adjust the Association weights by detecting the hits and misses and then pruning away the ones which prove irrelevant. To see this more clearly, right-click the “Association” module label (near the upper right of the network” and select “Show Dialog”. This dialog is another view into the UKS showing words across the top and various properties down the side. The highest-valued association is highlighted in green. The number is a relative weight of the association. To see the raw hits and misses, check the “Raw Value” checkbox. The system uses this information to build the “Inner Monologue” which is shown in the “Description Module Dialog”. You’ll see that for each new image, the description appears in the monologue. To watch the learning process again, right-click the UKS module tag and select “Initialize” to clear the content of the UKS. Now you can watch the association box add words and properties as they are encountered and rapidly converge on the correct associations. With more properties, the system takes longer to converge but unlike ANN learning, the system will converge in the minimum number of cycles needed to differentiate the associations correctly. The Relationship demonstration will be covered in the next software update.Current state of development:The UKS is reasonably robust. The system is a work in progress. Much of the image processing is placeholder code to be replaced with code from a library such as OpenCV in a subsequent release.
